article.description:
Shaquille O'Neal scored 42 points on 15-of-24
shooting and Kobe Bryant added 26 Monday night to lead the Los
Angeles Lakers to a 102-85 victory over the Los Angeles Clippers.
article.headline: Shaq scores 42 points against short-handed Clippers

images.name: O'Neal Shaquille 030317 Inline
images.caption: The Lakers' Shaquille O'Neal scored 42 points on 15-of-24 shooting.

article.linkText: Battle of Los Angeles: Shaq, Lakers too much for Clips
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Shaquille O'Neal scored 42 points and was a bit disappointed. "I was looking in the paper and saw I needed 53 points to reach the 20,000 mark. I was actually trying to get to that point tonight. I'd rather just get it out of the way,'' the Los Angeles Lakers center said Monday night after a 102-85 victory over the Los Angeles Clippers. O'Neal smiled and added, "Now I just have to get it against my favorite team.'' The Lakers' next game is Thursday at rival Sacramento. O'Neal and Kobe Bryant did most of the work for the Lakers against the Clippers, and that was plenty. O'Neal went 15-of-24 from the floor and 12-of-15 from the line, and Bryant added 26 points as the Lakers beat their city rivals for the 23rd time in their last 25 meetings. The rest of the Lakers combined for 34 points -- eight fewer than O'Neal alone. "We weren't very sharp tonight,'' coach Phil Jackson said. "I thought we were always deferring to Shaquille in the post and it allowed them to create difficult angles for us in the first half. "Some unforced turnovers helped the Clippers take an early lead, but we were ready to play the second half and came out and we were pretty precise about what we wanted to get done.'' The Lakers' reserves were outscored 21-11 and had zero points in the first half. "I liked Kobe's response when Shaquille came out of the game,'' Jackson said. "We had nothing off the bench, no scoring at all off the bench in the first half.'' Dennis Johnson, the Clippers' interim coach, said O'Neal and Bryant were simply too much. "When you have two great players like that, they are a tough tag team to guard,'' Johnson said. Holding a 78-76 lead with 6:58 remaining, the Lakers outscored the Clippers 24-9 the rest of the way. O'Neal had 13 points during the run. The Clippers, thinned by injuries, led until late in the third quarter but couldn't hold on and lost for the 18th time in 22 games. Andre Miller led the Clippers with 15 points, and Cherokee Parks and Quentin Richardson each added 13. "We got up on them by playing our 'A' game, which we showed we can do. But you've got to play your 'A' game consistently throughout the game, and we haven't done that yet,'' said Lamar Odom, who scored nine points for the Clippers in the first half and just three in the second. "In a game like this, we needed somebody to have a big game, whether it be Andre or myself. Andre played really well, but no one was able to get it going offensively.'' The Clippers led by as many as 14 late in the first half, but the Lakers chipped away and went up 68-66 on a behind-the-back pass from Bryant that led to a swooping dunk by O'Neal with 1:59 left in the third quarter. It was the Lakers' first lead since the opening moments of the game, and they stayed in front the rest of the way. Odom's 18-foot jumper gave the Clippers a 40-26 lead with 3:19 left in the second quarter, but the Lakers outscored them 9-1 to narrow the gap to 41-35 at halftime. Bryant drew a technical for jawing at referee Steve Javie after Javie called him for his second foul in a 27-second span late in the first half. Bryant smiled and shook his head as he walked away from the referee, then was whistled again for a charge a minute later -- 41 seconds before halftime. Jackson replaced Bryant with Brian Shaw. Game notes
O'Neal is looking to become the 28th player to score 20,000 points in a career. ... Clippers F Corey Maggette didn't play because of a sprained left ankle. He was hurt in a 111-110 victory over Toronto on Sunday night. ... Clippers F Elton Brand, out with a stress fracture in his left leg, said he wants to play again this season but needs a doctor's OK. He will undergo an MRI exam Friday. ... The Lakers lead the all-time series 119-38. ... Bryant hit the back of the rim to miss a driving dunk late in the game. Only 37 seconds later, the Clippers' Eric Piatkowski bounced the ball high off the heel of the rim exactly the same way.
